[{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"ENV[\"GKSwstype\"] = \"100\"\nENV[\"GKS_ENCODING\"]=\"utf8\"","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/#Kernel-Functions","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"A kernel function defines the smoothing behavior of the ASH estimator.  ","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"AverageShiftedHistograms can use any function as a kernel that satisifies the following properties:","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"Non-negative: f(x) >= 0\nSymmetric: f(x) = f(-x)","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"note: Note\nIn most applications, kernels need to integrate to 1, but that is not required in AverageShiftedHistograms","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/#Function-in-AverageShiftedHistograms.Kernels","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Function in AverageShiftedHistograms.Kernels","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"The Kernels module defines a collection of kernels:","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"biweight (default)\ncosine\nepanechnikov\ntriangular\ntricube\ntriweight\nuniform\ngaussian\nlogistic","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel(statistics)#Kernelfunctionsincommon_use for detailed descriptions.","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"kernels = [\n        Kernels.biweight,    \n        Kernels.cosine,      \n        Kernels.epanechnikov,\n        Kernels.triangular,  \n        Kernels.tricube,     \n        Kernels.triweight,   \n        Kernels.uniform,     \n        Kernels.gaussian,\n        Kernels.logistic\n    ]\n\nplot(kernels, -1.5, 1.5, line=(2, :auto), lab=permutedims(string.(kernels)))\n\nsavefig(\"kernels.png\")\n\nnothing","category":"page"},{"location":"kernels/","page":"Kernel Functions","title":"Kernel Functions","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"api/#API","page":"API","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api/","page":"API","title":"API","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"api/","page":"API","title":"API","text":"Modules = [AverageShiftedHistograms]","category":"page"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.ash!-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.ash!","text":"ash!(o::Ash; kw...)\nash!(o::Ash, newdata; kw...)\n\nUpdate an Ash estimate with new data, smoothing parameter (keyword m), or kernel (keyword kernel):\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.ash-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.ash","text":"Univariate Ash\n\nash(x; kw...)\n\nFit an average shifted histogram to data x.  Keyword options are:\n\nrng    : values over which the density will be estimated\nm      : Number of adjacent histograms to smooth over\nkernel : kernel used to smooth the estimate\n\nBivariate Ash\n\nash(x, y; kw...)\n\nFit a bivariate averaged shifted histogram to data vectors x and y.  Keyword options are:\n\nrngx    : x values where density will be estimated\nrngy    : y values where density will be estimated\nmx      : smoothing parameter in x direction\nmy      : smoothing parameter in y direction\nkernelx : kernel in x direction\nkernely : kernel in y direction\n\nMutating an Ash object\n\nAsh objectes can be updated with new data, smoothing parameter(s), or kernel(s).  They cannot, however, change the ranges over which the density is estimated.  It is therefore suggested to err on the side of caution when choosing data endpoints.\n\n# univariate\nash!(obj; kw...)\nash!(obj, newx, kw...)\n\n# bivariate\nash!(obj; kw...)\nash!(obj, newx, newy; kw...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.cdf-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash,Real}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.cdf","text":"cdf(o::Ash, x::Real)\n\nReturn the estimated cumulative density at the point x.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.extendrange","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.extendrange","text":"extendrange(x, s = .5, n = 200)\n\nCreate a range of length n starting at s standard deviations below minimum(x) and ending at s standard deviations above maximum(x)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.histdensity-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.histdensity","text":"return the histogram values as a density (integrates to 1)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.nout-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.nout","text":"return the number of observations that fell outside of the histogram range\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.pdf-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash,Real}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.pdf","text":"pdf(o::Ash, x::Real)\n\nReturn the estimated density at the point x.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.xy-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.xy","text":"return the range and density of a univariate ASH\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#AverageShiftedHistograms.xyz-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash2}","page":"API","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.xyz","text":"return ranges and density of biviariate ASH\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api/#StatsBase.nobs-Tuple{AverageShiftedHistograms.Ash}","page":"API","title":"StatsBase.nobs","text":"return the number of observations\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"ENV[\"GKSwstype\"] = \"100\"\nENV[\"GKS_ENCODING\"]=\"utf8\"","category":"page"},{"location":"#AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"An Average Shifted Histogram (ASH) estimator is essentially a kernel density estimator calculated over a fine-partition histogram.  ","category":"page"},{"location":"#Benefits-Over-KDE","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"Benefits Over KDE","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"The histogram component can be constructed on-line.\nAdding new data is an O(nbins) operation vs. O(n) for KDE, nbins << n.\nASH is considerably faster even for small datasets.  See below with a comparison with KernelDensity.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"julia> @btime kde(x) setup=(x=randn(100));\n  169.523 μs (106 allocations: 56.05 KiB)\n\njulia> @btime ash(x) setup=(x=randn(100));\n  4.173 μs (3 allocations: 8.22 KiB)\n  ```\n\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"@raw html <img width = 600 src = \"https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8075494/17938441/ce8815e4-69da-11e6-8f19-33052e2ef21e.gif\">","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"\n\n## Tutorial\n\nThe main function exported by **AverageShiftedHistograms** is `ash`.\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"@docs ash","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"\n### Univariate Example\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"@example index using AverageShiftedHistograms using Plots","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"y = randn(100_000)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"o = ash(y; rng = -5:.2:5)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"xy(o)  # return (rng, density)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"plot(plot(o), plot(o; hist=false), layout=(2,1)) savefig(\"plot1.png\")  # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"![](plot1.png)\n\n\n### Bivariate Example\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"@example index using AverageShiftedHistograms using Plots","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"x = randn(10000) y = x + randn(10000)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"o = ash(x, y)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"plot(o) savefig(\"bivariate.png\")  # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"\n![](bivariate.png)\n\n\n### Gotchas\n\n!!! warning\n    Beware oversmoothing by setting the `m` parameter too large.  Note that \"too large\" is relative\n    to the width of the bin edges.\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","title":"AverageShiftedHistograms.jl","text":"@example index o = ash(y; rng = -5:.1:5, m = 20) plot(o) savefig(\"plot2.png\")  # hide ``` (Image: )","category":"page"}]
